00:37:29.580 --> 00:37:31.791
I've been walking
through the hall. but actually

723
00:37:31.874 --> 00:37:34.460
in the studio for a class here.
it's been a while.

724
00:37:36.629 --> 00:37:40.758
It's like…
That was a lot of sweat in these floors.

725
00:37:41.384 --> 00:37:44.095
If somebody like lifted up
history out of these floors.

726
00:37:44.178 --> 00:37:46.847
it would be kinda gross. but inspiring.

727
00:37:48.266 --> 00:37:50.226
I played
the first Hot Chocolate Nutcracker

728
00:37:50.309 --> 00:37:51.769
in the first production.

729
00:37:53.813 --> 00:37:56.315
I left my biological family behind
when I was 13.

730
00:37:56.816 --> 00:37:59.777
My mother and my three sisters
moved to Arizona. and I--

731
00:38:00.278 --> 00:38:03.406
My mom made the conscious decision
to allow me to stay here.

732
00:38:04.240 --> 00:38:06.409
So I moved in
with Miss Harris. Mama Harris.

733
00:38:07.076 --> 00:38:10.079
and then I got full scholarship
in dance here.

734
00:38:10.162 --> 00:38:12.498
The first time
I was the Little Nutcracker. it felt like.

735
00:38:12.581 --> 00:38:15.793
"I'm-- I'm one of the principal roles. I--

736
00:38:16.627 --> 00:38:19.130
Oh. cool!"
It was. like. Miss Allen believed in me.

737
00:38:19.213 --> 00:38:21.132
[up-tempo classical music playing]

738
00:38:24.218 --> 00:38:26.804
Now. Ryan Phuong.
he's the Little Nutcracker.

739
00:38:40.526 --> 00:38:44.155
Thank God I did it first
because I would not wanna follow him.

740
00:38:44.238 --> 00:38:45.281
[chuckles]

741
00:39:01.797 --> 00:39:04.550
[Debbie] I want it to be magical.
You can't just go over here

742
00:39:04.633 --> 00:39:07.428
and hit fourth position
like a Degas statue.

743
00:39:07.511 --> 00:39:09.013
and go here.

744
00:39:09.096 --> 00:39:10.014
No!

745
00:39:10.097 --> 00:39:12.516
It's the Hot Chocolate Nutcracker. honey.

746
00:39:13.059 --> 00:39:15.811
Alive! It's like.
"Oh. my God. look at him!"

747
00:39:15.936 --> 00:39:17.563
[gasps. sighs] Oh!

748
00:39:17.646 --> 00:39:19.023
It's gotta be that.

749
00:39:19.106 --> 00:39:21.150
Look at me. Stop. Look at him!

750
00:39:21.233 --> 00:39:23.402
You're so busy looking at yourselves.

751
00:39:23.486 --> 00:39:25.571
Play the scene. [gasps]

752
00:39:26.155 --> 00:39:28.032
"Oh. my God. he's moving!

753
00:39:28.115 --> 00:39:29.533
Look at him! [gasps]

754
00:39:29.617 --> 00:39:31.786
Oh. my God. I touched him!
Oh. my God. he's coming!

755
00:39:31.869 --> 00:39:33.329
Oh. my God! Oh. my God! Okay.

756
00:39:33.829 --> 00:39:35.831
-[giggles]
-[all laugh]

757
00:39:35.915 --> 00:39:37.666
Oh. my God! Ah!"

758
00:39:37.750 --> 00:39:39.251
It should be like that.

759
00:39:39.335 --> 00:39:42.254
I came here for. like.
an open class. for hip-hop. right?

760
00:39:42.338 --> 00:39:44.590
I think it was Chantel.
she was teaching.

761
00:39:44.673 --> 00:39:47.426
and that was the only thing
I would ever do is hip-hop.

762
00:39:47.510 --> 00:39:49.345
I did not plan on doing ballet
or anything.

763
00:39:49.428 --> 00:39:51.806
This little boy.
I couldn't believe what I was seeing.

764
00:39:51.889 --> 00:39:52.890
I was like. "What?"

765
00:39:52.973 --> 00:39:54.392
[hip-hop music playing]

766
00:39:55.434 --> 00:39:58.604
You put that hip-hop music on.
you would see like this little tornado.

767
00:39:58.687 --> 00:40:01.357
like the little Tasmanian Devil. you know?
[chuckling]

768
00:40:04.485 --> 00:40:06.654
[Debbie] He's been every Nutcracker.

769
00:40:06.737 --> 00:40:10.491
He was the Littlest Nutcracker.
and now he's the young prince.

770
00:40:11.617 --> 00:40:14.870
Ryan thought he was trying
to just take some hip-hop classes.

771
00:40:14.954 --> 00:40:17.164
and that's how we reeled him in.

772
00:40:17.248 --> 00:40:19.166
We give them something that they want.

773
00:40:19.250 --> 00:40:22.378
but we teach them. in order to do that.
you gotta get this first.

774
00:40:22.461 --> 00:40:24.630
Ballet. I… You know. it's…

775
00:40:24.713 --> 00:40:27.508
For me. back then.
I thought only girls should do that.

776
00:40:27.591 --> 00:40:28.926
[classical music playing]

777
00:40:29.927 --> 00:40:32.638
I was really terrified to take class.

778
00:40:34.223 --> 00:40:36.725
[Giana] Ballet training. very tough.

779
00:40:36.809 --> 00:40:40.104
Who will go through the ballet training

780
00:40:40.187 --> 00:40:43.399
and finish that ballet training.

781
00:40:43.482 --> 00:40:47.278
they have strong personality
to go further.

782
00:40:48.320 --> 00:40:50.197
And Miss Allen told me.

783
00:40:50.948 --> 00:40:52.616
who she is.

784
00:40:52.700 --> 00:40:57.538
it's because she went through th--
that tough. strong ballet training.

785
00:41:00.291 --> 00:41:03.711
[Debbie] I went to the North Carolina
School of the Arts to audition.

786
00:41:03.794 --> 00:41:06.964
after I'd been trained
by the Houston Ballet Foundation.

787
00:41:07.465 --> 00:41:09.884
I was so hopeful about that.

788
00:41:09.967 --> 00:41:13.554
and they used me in the audition
to demonstrate.

789
00:41:13.637 --> 00:41:16.140
and when it was over.
I went to the man and said.

790
00:41:16.223 --> 00:41:19.435
"Well. I just wanna know. how--
when would we start?

791
00:41:19.518 --> 00:41:20.978
How is this gonna go?"

792
00:41:21.061 --> 00:41:23.355
And he told me
I was not gonna be accepted.

793
00:41:23.439 --> 00:41:25.733
and that I was not right for dance.

794
00:41:25.816 --> 00:41:28.444
and my body wasn't right.
and I should do something else.

795
00:41:28.527 --> 00:41:30.321
And It broke her spirit.

796
00:41:30.404 --> 00:41:32.531
And she stopped dancing for a year or two.

797
00:41:33.365 --> 00:41:35.201
[Debbie] It was very discouraging.

798
00:41:35.284 --> 00:41:38.078
He told me. you know.
"Definitely don't think about ballet.

799
00:41:38.162 --> 00:41:39.955
Just forget it." and. um…

800
00:41:40.414 --> 00:41:42.082
Wow. that was hard.

801
00:41:43.042 --> 00:41:46.128
So when I came back home
and it was time to go to college.

802
00:41:46.837 --> 00:41:48.756
I was accepted to Howard University.

803
00:41:49.381 --> 00:41:53.385
and so I was. like.
"Okay. I have to let the dance go.

804
00:41:53.469 --> 00:41:56.305
I love it. but it doesn't love me."

805
00:41:57.056 --> 00:41:58.265
And it was hard.

806
00:41:58.349 --> 00:42:02.937
My mom just was really brokenhearted
when I got off that plane.

807
00:42:03.020 --> 00:42:04.688
That was the hardest part.

808
00:42:05.773 --> 00:42:07.900
You know. when I got off that plane.

809
00:42:08.651 --> 00:42:11.862
and she was at the airport.
and she met me in tears.

810
00:42:12.571 --> 00:42:14.740
And she said. "Deborah. you failed."

811
00:42:16.909 --> 00:42:18.327
"Deborah. you failed."

812
00:42:23.207 --> 00:42:24.667
[inspirational music playing]

813
00:42:30.965 --> 00:42:34.134
My mom said. "You come home this summer.
you don't go and dance.

814
00:42:34.218 --> 00:42:37.137
I'm gonna save the money
that I've been putting aside

815
00:42:37.221 --> 00:42:38.847
to send you away to dance

816
00:42:39.431 --> 00:42:40.558
and buy a car."

817
00:42:40.641 --> 00:42:43.018
I'm like.
"No! No. Mom. no. No. I want to."

818
00:42:43.561 --> 00:42:46.105
And that was the summer
that I met Martha Graham

819
00:42:46.689 --> 00:42:48.274
and Meredith Monk

820
00:42:48.357 --> 00:42:49.817
and Twyla Tharp

821
00:42:49.900 --> 00:42:50.985
and Alvin Ailey.

822
00:42:51.068 --> 00:42:54.947
It was a new wave of dancers
who were breaking the traditional mold.

823
00:42:55.030 --> 00:42:57.658
doing something new and exciting.

824
00:42:57.741 --> 00:43:00.202
When I saw Alvin Ailey.
it was everything for me.

825
00:43:00.286 --> 00:43:03.664
I was like. "Child. take these snowshoes.
honey. put them somewhere else.

826
00:43:03.747 --> 00:43:06.375
I wanna dance about feelings."

827
00:43:13.799 --> 00:43:14.883
[rhythmic tapping]

828
00:43:18.721 --> 00:43:22.266
I've been trying
for years to f-- figure out

829
00:43:22.349 --> 00:43:27.104
what-- how could I really use
the language of tap in the show.

830
00:43:27.187 --> 00:43:29.231
This year. Savion Glover's coming.

831
00:43:30.858 --> 00:43:33.611
I've asked him to create
a piece called "The Train."

832
00:43:33.694 --> 00:43:37.156
[scatting on drumbeat]

833
00:43:37.239 --> 00:43:40.326
[Savion]
Miss Debbie Allen had an idea early on.

834
00:43:40.409 --> 00:43:42.620
and then she put that idea

835
00:43:43.287 --> 00:43:45.664
in my thought process.
and I was thinking about it

836
00:43:45.748 --> 00:43:47.458
for the whole time.
and then I came back.

837
00:43:47.541 --> 00:43:49.877
and. um. I was ready to go.

838
00:43:49.960 --> 00:43:53.589
And her idea was that. you know.
to get this train thing moving.

839
00:43:53.672 --> 00:43:55.841
to get us from one scene to the next.

840
00:44:00.387 --> 00:44:02.181
[Debbie] Thank you. Thank you!

841
00:44:02.264 --> 00:44:04.975
Beyond the choreography.
I just want them to come out

842
00:44:05.059 --> 00:44:06.518
with a sense of empowerment.

843
00:44:07.603 --> 00:44:10.939
a sense of greatness.
a sense of achievement.

844
00:44:11.023 --> 00:44:12.941
a sense of expression!

845
00:44:13.025 --> 00:44:18.072
This ability to think
about making someone think differently.

846
00:44:21.617 --> 00:44:23.035
[girl] That was just my style.

847
00:44:23.118 --> 00:44:25.746
He just told me
to freestyle at the beginning.

848
00:44:25.829 --> 00:44:30.292
and so I just created my own little thing
at the beginning and end.

849
00:44:38.550 --> 00:44:42.388
I wanna be just available
as a human being.

850
00:44:42.471 --> 00:44:47.017
and I like that exchange.
that allows me to learn from them.

851
00:44:48.352 --> 00:44:51.271
And hopefully. they learn from me.

852
00:44:51.355 --> 00:44:53.482
-[drumming]
-[cymbal crashes]

853
00:45:01.281 --> 00:45:02.741
[Debbie] We're gonna have a session--

854
00:45:02.825 --> 00:45:05.828
We're gonna start having sessions
during the week

855
00:45:06.453 --> 00:45:09.832
because. otherwise.
I don't think you're gonna get there.

856
00:45:09.915 --> 00:45:13.836
and I-- I need to rearrange
some of your places.

857
00:45:16.463 --> 00:45:19.133
And they're just
not getting the doll dance.

858
00:45:19.216 --> 00:45:23.429
and I don't want them
to be on stage and not look fantastic.

859
00:45:23.512 --> 00:45:26.765
I just got kicked out of "Dolls."
like my sister too.

860
00:45:26.849 --> 00:45:31.395
'Cause. um. she wants me
to be in the party scene.

861
00:45:34.606 --> 00:45:38.360
[Eartha loudly] So you've gotta be in it
from the very top.

862
00:45:38.861 --> 00:45:41.238
I can't be a monkey over here like this.

863
00:45:42.948 --> 00:45:43.907
[man] Ooh.

864
00:45:43.991 --> 00:45:45.659
I'm ready for fairies.

865
00:45:46.618 --> 00:45:49.621
so when y'all in that wings.
I want y'all like this.

866
00:45:50.164 --> 00:45:51.749
Ready to go!

867
00:45:52.458 --> 00:45:55.252
I need arms swinging.
What happened to that?

868
00:45:55.335 --> 00:45:59.339
[shouting] And a one. two. three. four.

869
00:45:59.423 --> 00:46:02.885
And a up. up. up. up.

870
00:46:02.968 --> 00:46:04.595
Yes. Tobal!

871
00:46:04.678 --> 00:46:05.637
[all cheering]

872
00:46:07.306 --> 00:46:09.850
[Eartha]
I need to make her a monkey. [laughs]

873
00:46:13.353 --> 00:46:16.482
-I'm the-- Yes!
-[male instructor laughing]

874
00:46:17.357 --> 00:46:20.110
[sighs] Come on. girl. get in there.

875
00:46:20.778 --> 00:46:22.654
-[dancers cheering]
-[Eartha laughs]

876
00:46:23.739 --> 00:46:25.991
I got the job of doing "Rainforest."

877
00:46:26.074 --> 00:46:30.204
and "Rainforest"
is one of the biggest production numbers

878
00:46:30.287 --> 00:46:31.163
in the show.

879
00:46:31.246 --> 00:46:33.457
[tribal music playing]

880
00:46:33.540 --> 00:46:36.710
[Debbie]
"Rainforest" is beautiful. Butterflies.

881
00:46:36.794 --> 00:46:39.087
monkeys. panthers.

882
00:46:39.922 --> 00:46:40.756
[panther roars]

883
00:46:41.673 --> 00:46:45.677
When you think about herds of animals
on the plains in Africa.

884
00:46:45.761 --> 00:46:48.597
the migration.
everyone's going in the same direction.

885
00:46:49.389 --> 00:46:52.601
and so there is a--
a journey that's taking place.

886
00:46:54.895 --> 00:46:57.439
Oh. my God. how big is the cast?

887
00:46:57.523 --> 00:46:59.691
You know. I don't wanna say it out loud!

888
00:46:59.775 --> 00:47:01.819
Delorse. my costumer. might slap me.

889
00:47:01.902 --> 00:47:03.570
When she saw the cast of people.

890
00:47:03.654 --> 00:47:06.907
she said. "Miss Allen. really?"
I'm like. "Yeah. Delorse."

891
00:47:06.990 --> 00:47:08.617
[loud chattering]

892
00:47:09.243 --> 00:47:11.328
Shh. No more talking. please.

893
00:47:11.411 --> 00:47:14.540
Who does not have a costume? Hm?

894
00:47:14.623 --> 00:47:16.959
[Delorse]
Well. we have a cast of almost 200.

895
00:47:18.043 --> 00:47:21.964
Each person is wearing.
you know. three-- two to three things.

896
00:47:22.047 --> 00:47:23.423
Some kids are wearing five.

897
00:47:24.341 --> 00:47:25.634
Okay. girls.

898
00:47:26.385 --> 00:47:28.095
She went to go get more costumes.

899
00:47:28.178 --> 00:47:31.223
[loudly] I still hear talking. Okay!

900
00:47:31.306 --> 00:47:33.892
We're just… It's a little busy.

901
00:47:33.976 --> 00:47:35.644
Everybody like their costumes?

902
00:47:35.727 --> 00:47:38.522
-[kids] Yes!
-Excellent.

903
00:47:38.605 --> 00:47:40.566
[Debbie] That's two people missing.

904
00:47:40.649 --> 00:47:42.317
Oh! One. two. There's two.

905
00:47:42.943 --> 00:47:45.028
-Who's missing?
-[costume helper] JoAnn and AuDrya.

906
00:47:45.112 --> 00:47:46.446
[Debbie] And where are they?

907
00:47:46.530 --> 00:47:48.574
Some lady was trying
to say JoAnn hit her car.

908
00:47:48.657 --> 00:47:50.784
but she didn't.
so they're on their way. [chuckles]

909
00:47:53.495 --> 00:47:56.832
I was eight
when I started at DADA.

910
00:47:57.875 --> 00:48:02.296
This year. I've been kinda like
getting there when I wanted to.

911
00:48:02.379 --> 00:48:04.923
like. just trying to be a teenager.
I guess.

912
00:48:05.007 --> 00:48:06.049
[Debbie shouts] JoAnn!

913
00:48:06.133 --> 00:48:08.176
You don't just walk in my rehearsal.
What happened?

914
00:48:08.802 --> 00:48:10.470
-For what?
-[JoAnn] Speeding.

915
00:48:10.554 --> 00:48:11.388
Stay here.

916
00:48:14.433 --> 00:48:15.934
One. plié.

917
00:48:16.018 --> 00:48:17.477
Go warm up at the bar.

918
00:48:17.561 --> 00:48:19.021
One. plié.

919
00:48:19.855 --> 00:48:22.566
And down. down…

920
00:48:22.649 --> 00:48:25.944
[JoAnn] Whenever I feel
that I let her down. it was very…

921
00:48:26.778 --> 00:48:28.822
[sighs] Like. it got to me every time.

922
00:48:28.906 --> 00:48:31.241
So. I'm like.
"Dang. I can't let her down no more.

923
00:48:31.325 --> 00:48:32.618
We can't have these talks.

924
00:48:32.701 --> 00:48:35.787
The next few talks we have to have
have to be good talks."

925
00:48:35.871 --> 00:48:40.208
[laughs] Like. instead of just
her telling me to get it together.

926
00:48:40.292 --> 00:48:41.668
It takes a lot.

927
00:48:42.294 --> 00:48:45.547
I don't know.
I think it comes down to heart and will

928
00:48:45.631 --> 00:48:48.467
and wanting it for yourself.
wanting something more.

929
00:48:49.217 --> 00:48:50.052
And…

930
00:48:51.011 --> 00:48:51.845
Yeah.

931
00:48:52.304 --> 00:48:53.805
Working your butt off.

932
00:48:53.889 --> 00:48:58.727
I'm trying to help you
learn professional work ethic.

933
00:48:58.810 --> 00:49:00.270
Say "work ethic."

934
00:49:00.354 --> 00:49:01.271
[dancers] Work ethic.

935
00:49:01.355 --> 00:49:02.564
Work ethic.

936
00:49:02.648 --> 00:49:03.732
[dancers] Work ethic.

937
00:49:03.815 --> 00:49:06.193
This should apply
to everything you do in life.

938
00:49:06.276 --> 00:49:09.363
Your homework.
how you do your work at school.

939
00:49:09.446 --> 00:49:10.405
what other jobs

940
00:49:10.489 --> 00:49:13.617
and other career aspirations
that you have.

941
00:49:13.700 --> 00:49:17.329
If you work in the post office.
if you are a teacher.

942
00:49:17.412 --> 00:49:20.123
if you are a maintenance person.

943
00:49:20.207 --> 00:49:22.709
if you work in Washington.

944
00:49:22.793 --> 00:49:25.462
your work ethic must be the same.

945
00:49:25.963 --> 00:49:30.133
If you work with children.
your work ethic should even be better.

946
00:49:30.217 --> 00:49:32.844
Adolescence is difficult.

947
00:49:33.345 --> 00:49:36.932
and it's sort of like
your mind leaves you for a bit

948
00:49:37.015 --> 00:49:39.142
and you're just sort of out in orbit.

949
00:49:39.226 --> 00:49:42.688
You're exploring yourself.
you're exploring things around you.

950
00:49:42.771 --> 00:49:47.067
but the fact that you have something
to go to three or four times a week

951
00:49:47.693 --> 00:49:49.820
and be responsible to

952
00:49:49.903 --> 00:49:51.446
helps you be responsible

953
00:49:51.530 --> 00:49:54.449
with your school work.
your homework. your chores at home.

954
00:49:54.533 --> 00:49:58.370
and it gives you a sense of gratitude.

955
00:49:58.453 --> 00:50:01.081
How do you think
you're going to get where we are?

956
00:50:01.164 --> 00:50:03.542
Where are you trying to go in life?

957
00:50:04.042 --> 00:50:07.170
Every day
is not just a rehearsal for Nutcracker.

958
00:50:07.254 --> 00:50:09.798
it's a rehearsal
for the rest of your life.

959
00:50:09.881 --> 00:50:11.216
You come in here late.

960
00:50:11.299 --> 00:50:14.511
that's where you're gonna be
on your next job. and you're fired.

961
00:50:15.012 --> 00:50:18.181
You walk into a Broadway show late.
you're fired.

962
00:50:18.682 --> 00:50:22.019
The understudy is on.
They don't care how much they like you.

963
00:50:22.102 --> 00:50:24.021
You're not professional.

964
00:50:24.104 --> 00:50:25.814
-Do you understand?
-[dancers] Yes.

965
00:50:25.897 --> 00:50:29.651
Every day is your rehearsal for life.
not just the Nutcracker.

966
00:50:29.735 --> 00:50:32.070
Take it seriously. Make it into something.

967
00:50:33.113 --> 00:50:35.532
We have a lot of work to do.
I wanted to see you…

968
00:50:35.615 --> 00:50:38.869
Look. we're not in a bad place.
but we have literally a month.

969
00:50:38.952 --> 00:50:42.205
which means we don't have a month
'cause we don't rehearse every day.

970
00:50:42.289 --> 00:50:44.416
-So this is your homework.
-Thank you. Miss Allen.

971
00:50:44.499 --> 00:50:45.834
[dancers] Thank you. Miss Allen.

972
00:50:45.917 --> 00:50:48.003
[Debbie shouts]
Don't come to my rehearsal late.

973
00:50:48.545 --> 00:50:51.423
Don't come to any rehearsal late again.
and I mean it.

974
00:50:51.506 --> 00:50:52.632
Thank you. Dismissed.

975
00:50:52.716 --> 00:50:55.135
-[dancers] Thank you. Miss Allen.
-Thank you. Miss Cathie.

976
00:50:55.218 --> 00:50:56.970
-Thank you.
-[Debbie] Yes.

977
00:50:57.054 --> 00:50:58.555
-Thank you.
-Yes.

978
00:50:59.264 --> 00:51:00.640
-Yes.
-Thank you.

979
00:51:00.724 --> 00:51:02.142
Don't come late. AuDrya.

980
00:51:02.768 --> 00:51:04.394
If you're late. just stay out.

981
00:51:04.478 --> 00:51:05.353
-Thank you.
-Yes.

982
00:51:05.437 --> 00:51:06.605
-Thank you. Miss Allen.
-Yes.

983
00:51:06.688 --> 00:51:08.273
-Thank you.
-Hmm!

984
00:51:08.899 --> 00:51:09.983
Mm-mm.

985
00:51:10.692 --> 00:51:12.277
-Thank you. Miss Allen.
-Yes.

986
00:51:12.360 --> 00:51:14.654
-Thank you. Miss Allen.
-More joy. You're beautiful.

987
00:51:14.738 --> 00:51:16.698
No. do you know how beautiful you are?

988
00:51:16.782 --> 00:51:18.158
I don't think you do.

989
00:51:18.241 --> 00:51:20.118
You're so beautiful.

990
00:51:20.702 --> 00:51:23.288
Embody that. Embrace that when you dance.

991
00:51:23.371 --> 00:51:24.206
Go away.

992
00:51:24.831 --> 00:51:25.665
Yes.

993
00:51:25.749 --> 00:51:27.667
Thank you. Get rid of those nails.

994
00:51:27.751 --> 00:51:29.628
-Thank you. Miss Allen.
-Yes.

995
00:51:29.711 --> 00:51:30.962
Thank you. You'll be doing it.

996
00:51:31.046 --> 00:51:37.469
[Karen] The window of opportunity
to enter in the dance world is small.

997
00:51:37.552 --> 00:51:40.097
You have to do it by a certain time.

998
00:51:40.180 --> 00:51:42.599
You have to pull yourself up

999
00:51:42.682 --> 00:51:47.395
in a way that. by the time
you definitely are out of high school.

1000
00:51:47.479 --> 00:51:50.065
you have to be able
to audition and compete.

1001
00:51:51.066 --> 00:51:55.779
April. you come from this side of stage.
and you basically tell them all to come.

1002
00:51:55.862 --> 00:51:58.698
[April]
I auditioned for Dance Theatre of Harlem.

1003
00:51:58.782 --> 00:52:01.827
and I wasn't accepted into the company.

1004
00:52:01.910 --> 00:52:03.578
Then I was auditioning for other places.

1005
00:52:03.662 --> 00:52:06.331
thinking that I would get in
somewhere else.

1006
00:52:06.414 --> 00:52:07.749
but it just didn't happen.

1007
00:52:09.292 --> 00:52:10.544
Like. as a dancer.

1008
00:52:10.627 --> 00:52:14.339
you're always trying
to find the next place to go

1009
00:52:14.422 --> 00:52:15.966
or trying to improve.

1010
00:52:16.049 --> 00:52:19.594
And sometimes. it feels like.
you know. you're just stuck auditioning

1011
00:52:19.678 --> 00:52:21.471
and not getting anything.

1012
00:52:21.555 --> 00:52:24.391
So. it's just. like.
the life of a dancer is very hard.

1013
00:52:24.474 --> 00:52:27.644
but. like. I can't imagine myself
doing anything else.

1014
00:52:29.104 --> 00:52:32.607
[Savoy] I applied to 12 schools.
I would always say. when I was younger.

1015
00:52:32.691 --> 00:52:35.402
I was like. "I'm applying for dance.
I don't have to do anything.

1016
00:52:35.485 --> 00:52:37.028
My grades don't matter.
Nothing matters.

1017
00:52:37.112 --> 00:52:39.823
I'm just gonna dance." And like. no.

1018
00:52:39.906 --> 00:52:41.658
Like. it's honestly. like. worse.

1019
00:52:42.242 --> 00:52:43.869
So. I'm freaking out a little bit.

1020
00:52:43.952 --> 00:52:49.332
It takes so much focus to succeed.

1021
00:52:49.416 --> 00:52:51.585
You can't let things get you down.

1022
00:52:51.668 --> 00:52:53.628
Whether your teacher is too mean.

1023
00:52:53.712 --> 00:52:55.213
or it's too easy.

1024
00:52:55.797 --> 00:52:58.383
you can't let it disturb you.

1025
00:52:58.466 --> 00:53:00.927
[Eartha] Six. hold. Up!

1026
00:53:01.011 --> 00:53:02.387
I need to learn that too…

1027
00:53:03.430 --> 00:53:06.183
because I do the same thing still.
You know what I mean?

1028
00:53:06.266 --> 00:53:09.519
I-- I-- I don't get a choreography job.
I'm immediately like.

1029
00:53:09.603 --> 00:53:12.314
"I'm not good enough. Forget it."
and I quit.

1030
00:53:12.397 --> 00:53:14.274
Up. eight.

1031
00:53:15.108 --> 00:53:18.486
We have to work hard at what we do.
I don't care if you're eight years old.

1032
00:53:18.570 --> 00:53:21.114
There's eight-year-old actors
and actresses in movies right now

1033
00:53:21.198 --> 00:53:22.741
that are doing huge scenes.

1034
00:53:23.575 --> 00:53:25.702
You have to be engaged.
it doesn't matter how young.

1035
00:53:25.785 --> 00:53:27.162
[jazzy music playing]

1036
00:53:29.331 --> 00:53:31.124
[JoAnn]
I wanted to be. like. a company dancer.

1037
00:53:31.208 --> 00:53:34.294
so I wanted to go to school.
train. train. train.

1038
00:53:34.377 --> 00:53:37.505
graduate. then. hopefully.
get into a company like Alvin Ailey.

1039
00:53:39.090 --> 00:53:43.136
Everybody has that dream.
Everybody wants to dance professionally.

1040
00:53:44.221 --> 00:53:46.223
You see that in Savoy.

1041
00:53:46.306 --> 00:53:48.391
You see that in April.

1042
00:53:48.475 --> 00:53:50.268
You see that in JoAnn.

1043
00:53:56.524 --> 00:53:58.735
[Eartha] Sometimes.
you see it in their eyes. like…

1044
00:53:59.694 --> 00:54:01.529
Are they gonna make it?
Are they gonna make it?

1045
00:54:01.613 --> 00:54:04.491
Come on. girl.
You can make it! You can make it!

1046
00:54:04.574 --> 00:54:08.536
And. uh. you know. I know a lot of people
who don't become dancers.

1047
00:54:08.620 --> 00:54:10.872
who are incredible surgeons.

1048
00:54:10.956 --> 00:54:13.458
but have dance still under their belt.

1049
00:54:16.086 --> 00:54:18.213
[Debbie]
Well. Steve Jobs took dance class.

1050
00:54:18.296 --> 00:54:19.339
He did.

1051
00:54:19.881 --> 00:54:23.927
He bailed out of his math class
to go and take dance class.

1052
00:54:24.970 --> 00:54:26.680
That says a lot to me.

1053
00:54:30.600 --> 00:54:33.770
Like. I wanna go to New York
and go to these schools.

1054
00:54:33.853 --> 00:54:36.273
but I don't think I can do it.
then my mom is like.

1055
00:54:36.356 --> 00:54:40.694
"Oh well. this Ailey scholarship audition
is coming up in New York. so…"

1056
00:54:41.945 --> 00:54:46.157
And I'm. "Wait. am I going? Are we going?"
She's like. "You and Savoy are."

1057
00:54:47.409 --> 00:54:50.704
I'm like. "Oh. wow."
So it's just us two. both 17…

1058
00:54:50.787 --> 00:54:52.872
[chuckles]
…getting on a plane by ourselves

1059
00:54:52.956 --> 00:54:55.333
and going to New York
to audition for this school.

1060
00:54:56.334 --> 00:54:58.003
And then I went to San Francisco

1061
00:54:58.086 --> 00:55:01.339
for LINES.
I felt really comfortable there.

1062
00:55:01.423 --> 00:55:03.174
Very comfortable.
So after I got a scholarship

1063
00:55:03.258 --> 00:55:04.884
to their summer program. it gave me hope.

1064
00:55:04.968 --> 00:55:06.344
"Maybe I can dance in my future."

1065
00:55:09.556 --> 00:55:11.933
-[instructor] Good job.
-[applauding]

1066
00:55:12.017 --> 00:55:16.521
Then after that. they were asking.
um. for. like. payment deadlines.

1067
00:55:16.604 --> 00:55:17.939
right after the intensive.

1068
00:55:21.860 --> 00:55:24.988
[woman] Housing for a month
in San Francisco is…

1069
00:55:25.071 --> 00:55:27.741
because they don't provide housing
at the intensives.

1070
00:55:27.824 --> 00:55:29.492
it's just off the chain.

1071
00:55:29.576 --> 00:55:30.994
And going to Ailey.

1072
00:55:31.077 --> 00:55:33.872
she wasn't awarded any scholarships.

1073
00:55:33.955 --> 00:55:36.833
so just for a summer.
to go to Ailey. or…

1074
00:55:37.709 --> 00:55:40.337
It was pretty close to.

1075
00:55:40.420 --> 00:55:42.630
with tuition and housing.

1076
00:55:43.131 --> 00:55:44.716
probably like six. seven grand.

1077
00:55:45.258 --> 00:55:46.426
And that's just not…

1078
00:55:47.677 --> 00:55:50.555
anything. as a single parent.
I-- I could ever afford.

1079
00:55:51.806 --> 00:55:55.352
Yeah. that's when I figured out.

1080
00:55:55.435 --> 00:55:57.228
"Okay. maybe dance isn't for me."

1081
00:55:58.229 --> 00:56:00.231
and things went left.

1082
00:56:00.315 --> 00:56:01.858
And then I was just like.

1083
00:56:02.776 --> 00:56:06.112
"Um. I need to find out
what I'm about to do

1084
00:56:06.196 --> 00:56:07.947
for the rest of my life." [chuckles]

1085
00:56:21.878 --> 00:56:23.463
[Chantel] See you on Wednesday.

1086
00:56:23.546 --> 00:56:24.422
[soft chattering]

1087
00:56:25.340 --> 00:56:26.174
[shushing]

1088
00:56:31.679 --> 00:56:34.391
[Terry] I started doing aerial
a long time ago. and Debbie was like.

1089
00:56:34.474 --> 00:56:36.559
"Okay.
how can we put aerial into the show?"

1090
00:56:36.643 --> 00:56:38.603
So. we started flying the Fairy Queen.

1091
00:56:40.772 --> 00:56:44.317
This year. Kylie Jefferson and April
were both the Fairy Queen.

1092
00:56:44.401 --> 00:56:47.112
but for my shows.
I mostly worked with Kylie.

1093
00:56:47.195 --> 00:56:51.324
Kylie's like a big sister to me.
I've always looked up to her.

1094
00:56:51.408 --> 00:56:55.745
She graduated from DADA
and went to Complexions.

1095
00:56:55.829 --> 00:56:58.623
one of the best
contemporary dance companies.

1096
00:56:58.706 --> 00:57:00.083
[Terry] Okay. boom! Hover.

1097
00:57:00.166 --> 00:57:04.087
I got into my dream company.
Complexions Contemporary Ballet.

1098
00:57:04.170 --> 00:57:06.756
[Terry] Down. Now…

1099
00:57:07.590 --> 00:57:11.261
[Kylie] I had been working
with the company for a few months.

1100
00:57:11.344 --> 00:57:14.013
I went over my partner's shoulder
for a lift.

1101
00:57:14.097 --> 00:57:18.393
and I just remember
hearing something. like. pop.

1102
00:57:19.102 --> 00:57:20.270
Crack. something.

1103
00:57:20.353 --> 00:57:23.606
It was a loud noise in my rib.

1104
00:57:23.690 --> 00:57:26.901
and I screamed onstage.

1105
00:57:26.985 --> 00:57:31.573
That was probably
the worst injury that I've ever had.

1106
00:57:33.032 --> 00:57:35.618
I came offstage. and I collapsed.

1107
00:57:36.327 --> 00:57:40.748
And I was just bawling
and in tears and in so much pain.

1108
00:57:42.584 --> 00:57:44.669
I thought it was over.

1109
00:57:44.752 --> 00:57:48.089
I kinda almost. like.
wanted it to be over.

1110
00:57:48.173 --> 00:57:52.343
I was like. "I don't wanna dance anymore."
My heart was so broken.

1111
00:57:53.386 --> 00:57:55.889
In this world.
there's gonna be a lot of pain.

1112
00:57:56.431 --> 00:58:00.226
Pain to your body.
but also it can be to your feelings.

1113
00:58:00.310 --> 00:58:04.397
But you have to pull up.
and you have to measure up to that.

1114
00:58:04.481 --> 00:58:07.442
You have to get-- like the athletes.
you have to stay in the game.

1115
00:58:07.525 --> 00:58:08.735
Are you gonna stay in the game?

1116
00:58:08.818 --> 00:58:09.777
Okay.

1117
00:58:10.361 --> 00:58:13.573
[shouts] Quiet! Shh.
Quiet! We're starting all over.

1118
00:58:14.449 --> 00:58:15.825
Music. go.

1119
00:58:16.618 --> 00:58:17.911
[uplifting music playing]

1120
00:58:18.495 --> 00:58:20.205
Bounce. bounce. bounce.

1121
00:58:20.997 --> 00:58:23.500
Bounce. bounce. bounce. happy.

1122
00:58:23.583 --> 00:58:25.418
Happy. right from the beginning.

1123
00:58:25.502 --> 00:58:27.962
Character's as important as the dancing.

1124
00:58:28.046 --> 00:58:31.216
And that's part of being onstage.
that's part of being a professional

1125
00:58:31.299 --> 00:58:33.760
is the entire package

1126
00:58:33.843 --> 00:58:37.680
that I'm trying to help them touch
and understand what it is.

1127
00:58:40.433 --> 00:58:44.521
[Karen] The party scene
pretty much involves everyone in the cast.

1128
00:58:44.604 --> 00:58:49.067
so rehearsing the party scene
is pretty amazing.

1129
00:58:49.150 --> 00:58:52.195
[kids] ♪ This is Christmas. ooh… ♪

1130
00:58:52.278 --> 00:58:54.113
[Debbie] Yes. Sophia. yes!

1131
00:58:54.197 --> 00:58:55.114
[laughs]

1132
00:58:55.198 --> 00:58:57.325
♪ We can. can. can… ♪

1133
00:58:57.408 --> 00:58:59.911
[Debbie] And up! Down! Down! Up!

1134
00:58:59.994 --> 00:59:03.665
[Karen] We don't have enough space here.
We need ten studios. really.

1135
00:59:05.250 --> 00:59:08.586
[Debbie shouting]
No talking! There's no talking!

1136
00:59:09.504 --> 00:59:11.381
[Karen] We always remind the students

1137
00:59:11.965 --> 00:59:15.760
that it's their dream
that we're helping them shape.

1138
00:59:15.843 --> 00:59:19.138
It means nothing if they don't respect it.

1139
00:59:19.222 --> 00:59:20.223
Quiet!

1140
00:59:20.932 --> 00:59:24.435
-[Debbie] You come out…
-[Cathie] Shh! Shh!

1141
00:59:24.978 --> 00:59:26.813
Could you all shut up?

1142
00:59:26.896 --> 00:59:28.189
My God.

1143
00:59:28.273 --> 00:59:30.900
I mean. if I could just fire
some of you right now.

1144
00:59:30.984 --> 00:59:32.485
it would make my life easier.

1145
00:59:33.111 --> 00:59:35.863
I'm trying to get you ready
for the professional world.

1146
00:59:35.947 --> 00:59:39.742
You won't work anywhere
the way you act in this room.

1147
00:59:40.743 --> 00:59:44.247
I don't care who you are.
I don't care what your role is.

1148
00:59:44.330 --> 00:59:47.250
Talk while I'm working. and you are fired!

1149
00:59:48.209 --> 00:59:50.837
If that doesn't mean
anything to you. great.

1150
00:59:51.462 --> 00:59:52.422
We'll find out.

1151
00:59:52.505 --> 00:59:54.090
We're gonna find out right now.

1152
00:59:54.173 --> 00:59:57.176
The rest of this rehearsal.
talk one more time.

1153
01:00:00.847 --> 01:00:03.308
You're so disrespectful
to all these professionals here

1154
01:00:03.391 --> 01:00:05.226
trying to make this show incredible.

1155
01:00:05.810 --> 01:00:07.437
I'm trying to do your bows.

1156
01:00:07.520 --> 01:00:10.565
[silence]

1157
01:00:10.648 --> 01:00:13.568
This is how it should sound all the time.
like this.

1158
01:00:13.651 --> 01:00:16.696
That's how it should sound. like that.

1159
01:00:23.953 --> 01:00:26.581
Miss Allen's nice… to me.

1160
01:00:27.373 --> 01:00:30.335
I don't know about all the rest of them
'cause they bad.

1161
01:00:31.044 --> 01:00:34.297
She don't know I'm bad.
She know I got in trouble once.

1162
01:00:34.380 --> 01:00:36.716
She didn't yell at me. though.
but she like me.

1163
01:00:36.799 --> 01:00:38.801
I like Miss Allen. She nice.

1164
01:00:39.427 --> 01:00:40.845
[nostalgic music playing]

1165
01:00:42.096 --> 01:00:45.016
[Debbie] When Madame Semenova
was teaching me at Houston Ballet.

1166
01:00:45.099 --> 01:00:46.476
do you think we would talk?

1167
01:00:47.101 --> 01:00:52.315
Do you think I would open my mouth
to speak when she's talking?

1168
01:00:53.608 --> 01:00:56.611
Oh. my God. she taught with that cane.
She would whack you.

1169
01:00:56.694 --> 01:01:01.407
That's why I taught with a cane on Fame.
in tribute to Madame Tatiana Semenova.

1170
01:01:02.950 --> 01:01:06.287
You know. she lived long enough
to see me become very successful

1171
01:01:06.371 --> 01:01:09.165
on Broadway and television.

1172
01:01:09.707 --> 01:01:12.460
and I remember our last lunch together.

1173
01:01:12.543 --> 01:01:15.004
Madame opened a bottle of champagne…

1174
01:01:16.339 --> 01:01:18.091
and she told me I had to keep the cork

1175
01:01:18.174 --> 01:01:20.385
because that was good luck.
I still have the cork.

1176
01:01:21.135 --> 01:01:23.680
We sat. and she pulled out
the programs she had saved.

1177
01:01:23.763 --> 01:01:26.933
programs with my name
and other students' names

1178
01:01:27.016 --> 01:01:29.102
that she had trained and loved.

1179
01:01:30.520 --> 01:01:33.481
And as we were drinking the champagne
and eating.

1180
01:01:33.564 --> 01:01:37.318
she says. "Well. you know.
I had to find you-- I had to find you."

1181
01:01:37.402 --> 01:01:39.112
I said. "What do you mean?" She says.

1182
01:01:39.195 --> 01:01:44.867
"Well. we would not keep the Ford grant
if we did not diversify the students.

1183
01:01:44.951 --> 01:01:47.161
I needed to find a Black student."

1184
01:01:49.080 --> 01:01:52.083
And I sat there.
and it kind of took me aback

1185
01:01:53.376 --> 01:01:54.544
because I was like…

1186
01:01:56.129 --> 01:01:58.589
I thought I was chosen
because I was really good.

1187
01:01:59.215 --> 01:02:00.591
not because I was Black.

1188
01:02:02.844 --> 01:02:05.346
But then I thought about it. and I said.

1189
01:02:06.222 --> 01:02:07.265
"I was good."

1190
01:02:10.643 --> 01:02:14.689
[Karen] We have two
and a half days in the theater

1191
01:02:14.772 --> 01:02:16.649
to get ready for opening night.

1192
01:02:16.733 --> 01:02:18.651
[Cathie] Are you on the line?
Are you on the line?

1193
01:02:18.735 --> 01:02:22.321
Load-in has to happen first.
then everybody's trying to get-- wonder.

1194
01:02:22.405 --> 01:02:24.198
"When are we getting on stage for tech?"

